			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64185471">		
		on Wednesday January 24, 2024 @02:38PM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23203713&amp;cid=64185471">#64185471</a>)
		<small><a href="http://archive.org/" title="http://archive.org/" class="user_homepage_display">Homepage</a> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64185471">Great work by the investigators here!  I enjoyed reading through the <a href="https://forbetterscience.com/2024/01/02/dana-farberications-at-harvard-university/" title="forbetterscience.com">specific examples</a> [forbetterscience.com] they found.  There are a few that looked like people making mistakes with matplotlib and not catching it; a bunch that looked like people deliberately filling in missing sequence info with other data; and a few that are just baffling (little possibility it was a mistake; but also no obvious reason to fake that specific data).  A bit of a shitshow, and clearly unacceptable.

I mostly hope that this nonsense hasn't negatively impacted too much research and progress, and that the professional repercussions are appropriate.</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64185471">
